<subSubSection id="58855F6A305688FA11F7B4643C3DB219" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="7E899790B27FA7154515BEBAE37614EF" pageNumber="9">
In a recent taxonomic revision of this genus Cuezzo (2000) recognizes three species from the Nearctic region: 
<taxonomicName id="FFA1AFA53423BF7DAB407BD8CF4EAA6C" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29038" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius mccooki (McCook)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mccooki">F. mccooki (McCook</taxonomicName>
1880), 
<taxonomicName id="4DA90E0A1DE03887F222DB6D7E1CA69B" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29041" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius pruinosus (Roger)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pruinosus">F. pruinosus (Roger</taxonomicName>
1863a) and 
<taxonomicName id="0D5C038C4391C3CDCE64E968A3F28D34" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:175166" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius analis (André)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analis">
F. analis (
<normalizedToken id="E0D91902D7285F01AAE5DC985B4CC193" originalValue="André">Andre</normalizedToken>
</taxonomicName>
1893b), with the last-named being removed from synonymy under 
<taxonomicName id="1FD03D28FF677542D6134A0D121843B3" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29041" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius pruinosus (Roger)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pruinosus">F. pruinosus</taxonomicName>
. All three species are recorded by Cuezzo (2000) from California. 
<taxonomicName id="2E4C6BC7D3824A02FE71363F142AE32C" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29038" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius mccooki (McCook)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mccooki">F. mccooki</taxonomicName>
can be recognized by its abundant standing pilosity, but 
<taxonomicName id="6329A71EBC9F16600F33FCFCD411713B" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29041" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius pruinosus (Roger)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pruinosus">F. pruinosus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="AF275C8E7E3F8211BE104910534FBAC5" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:175166" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius analis (André)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analis">F. analis</taxonomicName>
cannot be reliably distinguished using the differences cited by Cuezzo (2000). In Cuezzo’s worker key 
<taxonomicName id="75A78D8A668760CA5B2694BD4AF55364" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:175166" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius analis (André)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analis">F. analis</taxonomicName>
is separated from 
<taxonomicName id="480455CB6774DD2CB40CEBEEF5A97A78" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29041" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius pruinosus (Roger)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pruinosus">F. pruinosus</taxonomicName>
based on the shape of the posterior margin of the head: concave (“sometimes…weak”) in 
<taxonomicName id="749BA7CB19E67A351B09E9369C03A33A" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:175166" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius analis (André)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analis">F. analis</taxonomicName>
, and straight in 
<taxonomicName id="9A6F587EEB9F943AE3692689445E68D1" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29041" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius pruinosus (Roger)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pruinosus">F. pruinosus</taxonomicName>
. Yet, this putative difference is contradicted by Cuezzo’s description of the 
<taxonomicName id="B271D358F9184A59E3FA9AC42701F772" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:175166" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius analis (André)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analis">F. analis</taxonomicName>
worker -where the posterior margin is said to vary from convex to weakly concave -and by the illustration of a 
<taxonomicName id="3F6F0F895446F97FD0AC9CEDC7B1337C" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:175166" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius analis (André)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analis">F. analis</taxonomicName>
worker (Cuezzo 2000, figure 10) which shows a posterior margin that is convex. (
<taxonomicName id="95A89F90B938B1E37C568646D5A3279B" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29041" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius pruinosus (Roger)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pruinosus">F. pruinosus</taxonomicName>
is described, and illustrated, as having the posterior margin of the head straight.) After examining a large series of 
<taxonomicName id="6B01F3FEF19E500F539E2C1332DC82F5" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2468" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Forelius</taxonomicName>
from the United States and northern Mexico I can find no consistent difference in worker head shape: the posterior margin of the head varies continuously from weakly convex through straight to weakly concave. Color is also variable, ranging from dark brown to yellowish-orange. Some nest series contain both light and dark-colored workers. It is possible that the California populations are not conspecific with 
<taxonomicName id="20DE2A8E68392268A200AA34C3E8304E" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29041" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius pruinosus (Roger)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pruinosus">F. pruinosus</taxonomicName>
(described from Cuba), but these and other western samples seem to grade insensibly into material from farther east and south, including populations in Florida and the West Indies with consistently dark and densely pubescent workers, which correspond to 
<taxonomicName id="78A00274AD26443C72083777E8FD4F3F" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29041" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius pruinosus (Roger)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pruinosus">F. pruinosus</taxonomicName>
(s.s.). The complex needs further study but because reliable diagnostic differences have not yet been uncovered I treat 
<taxonomicName id="A3CACEF9EC101754199DFCB2C17F1864" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:175166" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius analis (André)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analis">F. analis</taxonomicName>
(type locality Chihuahua, Mexico) as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="E0C48158954D850BC37E27A59AED7595" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29041" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius pruinosus (Roger)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pruinosus">F. pruinosus</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicNameLabel id="154522D9BAD2EFE386DAB29B2C295724">syn. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
), thus returning to the conventional treatment of these two names.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1763583EE217FEA6DE1699CF7E2B0F19" pageNumber="9">
It should be noted that even the distinction between 
<taxonomicName id="9644C7654BD6AA088DAC779AA3173B77" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29038" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius mccooki (McCook)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mccooki">F. mccooki</taxonomicName>
(standing hairs present on scapes, posterior margin of head, and external face of tibiae) and 
<taxonomicName id="D3757836F2B735CC4C35C05E9CB70887" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29041" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius pruinosus (Roger)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pruinosus">F. pruinosus</taxonomicName>
(standing hairs absent or very sparse on the afore-mentioned structures) occasionally breaks down in western North America, with workers from some localities showing intermediate amounts of pilosity. There is, however, a third distinct (and apparently undescribed) species of 
<taxonomicName id="9DE289D7C1D7FE6CBC95173A1354D41C" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2468" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Forelius</taxonomicName>
in the United States. It is small and dark with a conspicuously shiny mesepisternum, short scapes (SL 0.40-0.48), and sparse standing pilosity. This species ranges from southern Texas to Colombia, and has been found sympatrically with a larger 
<taxonomicName id="3F76D51BC43A44468B497482BDFA7AE9" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2468" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Forelius</taxonomicName>
species -apparently 
<taxonomicName id="4E5C553F4E195D53BFE016F69D1DD8D3" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29041" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius pruinosus (Roger)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pruinosus">F. pruinosus</taxonomicName>
-in Mexico, Guatemala and Costa Rica, without showing any sign of intergradation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="92E76FE56120F655938F78C668A34548" lastPageNumber="10" pageNumber="9">
As a nomenclatural side note, the author of 
<taxonomicName id="73187555CC864C985DECC14ED24D149A" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29038" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius mccooki (McCook)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mccooki">Forelius mccooki</taxonomicName>
is McCook not Forel, since McCook’s 1880 paper provides in his own words a sufficient “description or definition ” (ICZN, Article 12) of the ants to make the name available, prior to Forel’s (1886b) more detailed description of the same material. In addition, the date of publication of McCook’s paper is 1880 (Ward et al. 1996: 275), not 1879 as cited by Bolton (1995b) and others. Cuezzo’s (2000) attribution of authorship of 
<taxonomicName id="94D1F1FECA08892968D36CA37D8C675E" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29038" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Forelius" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Forelius mccooki (McCook)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mccooki">F. mccooki</taxonomicName>
to Forel is incorrect, but her designation of a lectotype from among material in the Forel collection in MHNG may be considered justifiable, to the extent that Forel’s specimens came from McCook and were part of the material to which McCook referred in his 1880 paper.
</paragraph>
